T1  - Incentive-Based Lending Capacity, Competition and Regulation in Banking
AU  - Chiesa, Gabriella
JO  - Journal of Financial Intermediation
VL  - 10
IS  - 1
SP  - 28
EP  - 53
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/01/01/
SN  - 1042-9573
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1006/jfin.2000.0306
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1042957300903061
AB  - This paper studies moral hazard in banking due to delegated monitoring in an environment of aggregate risk and examines its implications for credit market equilibrium and regulation, in a model where banks are price competitors for loans and deposits. It provides a rationale for an incentive-based lending capacity positively linked to the bank's capital and profit margin, for an oligopolistic market structure wherever banks have market power, and for capital requirements. Social-welfare-maximizing capital requirements are lowered in recessions, are higher the more fragmented the banking sector, and are increased when anti-competitive measures are removed. In equilibrium banks earn excessive profits and credit may be rationed. Journal of Economic Literature Classification Numbers: D82, G28, L13.
